{"type":"message","id":"4db006ec","parentId":"b731db77","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:25:50.464Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_3qme9pndmy3q_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\"confluence-dtlx\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"-y\",\n        \"confluence-mcp-server\"\n      ],\n      \"env\": {\n        \"CONF_MODE\": \"cloud\",\n        \"CONF_BASE_URL\": \"https://YOUR-DOMAIN.atlassian.net/wiki\",\n        \"CONF_USERNAME\": \"your-email@company.com\",\n--\n    \"confluence-qlhv\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"-y\",\n        \"confluence-mcp-server\"\n      ],\n      \"env\": {\n        \"CONF_MODE\": \"cloud\",\n        \"CONF_BASE_URL\": \"https://YOUR-DOMAIN.atlassian.net/wiki\",\n        \"CONF_USERNAME\": \"your-email@company.com\","}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":67,"aggregated":"\"confluence-dtlx\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"-y\",\n        \"confluence-mcp-server\"\n      ],\n      \"env\": {\n        \"CONF_MODE\": \"cloud\",\n        \"CONF_BASE_URL\": \"https://YOUR-DOMAIN.atlassian.net/wiki\",\n        \"CONF_USERNAME\": \"your-email@company.com\",\n--\n    \"confluence-qlhv\": {\n      \"command\": \"npx\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"-y\",\n        \"confluence-mcp-server\"\n      ],\n      \"env\": {\n        \"CONF_MODE\": \"cloud\",\n        \"CONF_BASE_URL\": \"https://YOUR-DOMAIN.atlassian.net/wiki\",\n        \"CONF_USERNAME\": \"your-email@company.com\",","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776255950425}}
{"type":"message","id":"f5565550","parentId":"4db006ec","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:25:59.321Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the original HEAD already uses `CONF_BASE_URL` and `CONF_USERNAME`! So my Python script didn't actually change those - the Python script was modifying `CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL` → `CONF_BASE_URL` etc., but the original HEAD already has `CONF_BASE_URL` and `CONF_USERNAME`. \n\nThe Python script was modifying:\n- `CONFLUENCE_BASE_URL` → `CONF_BASE_URL` \n- `CONFLUENCE_API_TOKEN` → `CONF_TOKEN`\n- `CONFLUENCE_EMAIL` → `CONF_USERNAME`\n\nBut looking at HEAD, the template already uses `CONF_BASE_URL` and `CONF_USERNAME`! So my Python script didn't actually need to change those. \n\nBut the Python script ran and reported changes anyway - I think the real issue is just formatting. Python's `json.dump` with `indent=2` reformats the entire file, so even though the data itself didn't change, the diff looks massive because of the whitespace differences. The key env vars were already correct in the original HEAD, so my Python script didn't actually introduce any real changes - it just reformatted the JSON. Let me check what the original file looked like to confirm.","thinkingSignature":"e04a14d21d937754e84791fd088e563641d82254ad9a2d940dc18e5e0e70ee45"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_bdrkod2fuo4e_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd /root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review && git show HEAD:ahv-openclaw-setup/configs/team-dev.json | python3 -c \"import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); mcp=d.get('mcp',{}); servers=mcp.get('servers',{}); [print(k, servers[k].get('env',{})) for k in servers if 'confluence' in k.lower()]\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":298,"output":365,"cacheRead":38609,"cacheWrite":672,"totalTokens":39944,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":177