{"type":"message","id":"bdd271e7","parentId":"1cf15870","timestamp":"2026-04-15T12:45:24.790Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to create a complete setup package for OpenClaw and push it to a separate branch. This should include:\n- Full skills\n- All 34 agents with their files\n- References\n- Everything needed for a new user to get started\n\nLet me think about what this means:\n1. The current setup package in `ahv-openclaw-setup/` exists but the user wants a more complete setup\n2. They want it pushed to a different branch (not main)\n3. It should include skills, agents, and references\n\nThe key insight here is: the current setup repo (github.com/maiychrus25/setup-openclaw) is what gets cloned when users run the install command. \n\nSo I need to structure the ahv-openclaw-setup directory with the shell script for installation, the Node.js setup logic, team configurations, and then copy over all the skill definitions and agent definitions from the v4-ecosystem-review workspace into this package so everything's self-contained and ready to go. I'll need to figure out the Git workflow for pushing this to a separate branch.\n\nThe core task is to build out a complete setup package with all skills, agents, configs, and dependencies included, then push it to a new branch for the team to use.\n\nThe setup repository already has the foundation with the install script, configuration templates, and a skills pack, but it's missing the actual agent definition files and the skills are encrypted rather than plain text. The core issue is that when cloning the repo to a different machine, those agent definition files won't be available locally, so the setup script can't find them. I need to figure out what files are actually missing from the repository versus what's in the backup, and then add those to the setup repo so the installation process works independently of any local files. I see the issue now—the agent definiti